:=        Hoverscript

:==          General

                Hoverscript is a lightweight markup language, inspired by Markdown and AsciiDoc.

:p:center/      It is intended to be used for writing structured documents, with headings, lists, paragraphs,
                                             quotes, tables, images, links, etc.

:===            Document structure

                   A document is a list of blocks of several types.

:q
                      There is a default "paragraph" block, which is used when the block type is not
                      specified. The paragraph is simply made up of lines of text, followed by a blank
                      line, or by the beginning of another block, indicated by a marker.
:q
:===            Indentation

                   Indentation has no meaning, it is ignored by the parser. It is used for readability of the
                   source file. There is a special case for verbatim blocks (see below)

:===            Block marker

                   A line that starts (first non-empty character) with a ":" indicates a new block. The block
                   type is indicated by the word that follows the ":".

                   We have either:
:verbatim
:*                 a block type without parameters, in which case we can write ":blocktype", for example
                   ":para",
:*                 a block type with named parameters, ":blocktype: par1=val1 par2=val2/" (note that it is not
                   :blocktype par1=val1 par2=val2/, the ":" after the block type is mandatory)
:*                 a block type with simple parameters, ":blocktype: val1 val2/". In this case, the meaning of
                   the parameters is defined by the block type and the parameter position
:verbatim

                   There can be synonyms for common block types, with usual parameters:

                   For example, heading blocks have as a fundamental parameter the title **level** (1 to 6).
:*                 A level 1 heading block can be shorten by using simply ":=" or ":h:1/" or ":h: level=1/".
:*                 A level 2 heading block can be indicated by: ":==" or ":h:2/" or ":h: level=2/".

:===            Block marker parameters

                   We can also specify block marker parameters by indicating them on the line **preceding**
                   the block marker.

                   A parameter line has the form "[par1=val1, par2=val2, ...]". Spaces can be put before and
                   after the options, but nothing else should appear on the line

                   For example, we can indicate the level of a heading by ":h:1/" or by
:verbatim
                   [level=1]
                   :h This is a level 1 title
:verbatim

:===            Blank lines

                   A line is said to be blank if it contains no characters or only "white" characters: spaces,
                   tabs.

